WEBVTT

1
00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:44.750
THE CLASS

2
00:01:24.830 --> 00:01:26.170
Hi.

3
00:01:26.340 --> 00:01:28.040
- Okay, François?
- And you?


4
00:01:28.210 --> 00:01:29.880
Stéphane. François.

5
00:01:31.050 --> 00:01:34.550
- Still on the team?
- As ready as ever.


6
00:01:40.890 --> 00:01:42.390
Hello.

7
00:01:46.520 --> 00:01:47.560
This one?

8
00:01:47.730 --> 00:01:50.360
At the back, please.

9
00:01:59.870 --> 00:02:02.580
Hi, I'm Hervé.

10
00:02:02.750 --> 00:02:05.420
A sports teacher here
for three years.


11
00:02:06.210 --> 00:02:09.210
Welcome to all our new colleagues.

12
00:02:09.380 --> 00:02:11.210
The students can be tough...

13
00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:14.630
...but they're good kids.

14
00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:19.760
Hi, I'm Olivier.
I teach physical science...


15
00:02:19.930 --> 00:02:22.890
...and I've been here for four years.

16
00:02:24.230 --> 00:02:25.770
I'm Patrick...

17
00:02:25.940 --> 00:02:29.480
...and I teach multiplication tables...

18
00:02:29.650 --> 00:02:31.820
...and sometimes mathematics.

19
00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:36.150
I've been at this school
for a number of years.


20
00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:37.410
Hello, I'm Anne.

21
00:02:37.570 --> 00:02:42.410
I used to work in the Lyon suburbs.
I teach English.


22
00:02:42.580 --> 00:02:45.120
I'm looking for my new colleagues.

23
00:02:45.290 --> 00:02:46.960
Hi, I'm Isabelle.

24
00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:49.750
I'm Christiane.

25
00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:53.420
I'm Frédéric,
I teach history and geography...


26
00:02:53.590 --> 00:02:56.930
...and I used to work
out in the suburbs of Paris.


27
00:02:57.260 --> 00:02:59.930
I'm happy to be in the city now.

28
00:03:01.260 --> 00:03:03.310
I'm Julie, the year supervisor.

29
00:03:03.470 --> 00:03:07.100
I'd like to welcome you all
and wish you a good year.


30
00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:10.230
I'm Aline and I'm the cook.

31
00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:12.980
I'd like to welcome you all.

32
00:03:13.150 --> 00:03:14.940
Thank you, Aline.

33
00:03:16.650 --> 00:03:19.280
Hello. I'm Gilles.

34
00:03:19.570 --> 00:03:24.620
I've been teaching mathematics
for many years.


35
00:03:24.790 --> 00:03:27.620
I'm retiring at the end of this year.

36
00:03:27.790 --> 00:03:32.670
I'd like to wish the new arrivals
plenty of courage.


37
00:03:36.550 --> 00:03:38.010
I'm François.

38
00:03:38.180 --> 00:03:42.140
I teach French
and I'm starting my fourth year here.


39
00:03:42.390 --> 00:03:44.310
Welcome, everybody.

40
00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:55.610
We'll all meet up at midday...

41
00:03:55.820 --> 00:03:58.990
...in the canteen for a drink
to mark the new year.


42
00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:13.670
You get Wednesday like you wanted.

43
00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:16.210
We could swap our classes.

44
00:04:19.550 --> 00:04:21.550
Nice, nice.

45
00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:24.260
Not nice, not nice at all.

46
00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:25.890
He's nice.

47
00:04:26.060 --> 00:04:29.060
Not nice, watch him, not nice at all.

48
00:04:29.230 --> 00:04:31.890
Nice, not nice.

49
00:04:32.150 --> 00:04:34.020
She's not nice at all.

50
00:04:42.030 --> 00:04:44.410
Arthur, your cap.

51
00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:48.080
Good morning.

52
00:04:50.540 --> 00:04:51.750
That's my place.

53
00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:53.500
Get lost.

54
00:05:23.780 --> 00:05:25.910
Calm down now.

55
00:05:28.410 --> 00:05:29.790
Stop stirring things up.

56
00:05:29.950 --> 00:05:32.410
Remove your hood, please.

57
00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:35.420
You two back there,
there's a place here.


58
00:05:35.580 --> 00:05:37.880
- One up front.
- There's room here too.


59
00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:40.630
Let's get one thing clear.

60
00:05:46.300 --> 00:05:49.060
We waste five minutes
lining up outside...


61
00:05:49.220 --> 00:05:53.890
...five coming up, five settling down:

62
00:05:54.060 --> 00:05:56.940
Do you realize
what 15 lost minutes means?


63
00:05:57.110 --> 00:05:58.440
With 25 hours a week...

64
00:05:58.610 --> 00:06:02.490
...and 30 weeks in the year,
we lose thousands of minutes.


65
00:06:02.990 --> 00:06:05.490
In other schools, they do a full hour.

66
00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:08.780
Imagine how far ahead
they get in a year.

67
00:06:10.580 --> 00:06:11.990
Figure it out.

68
00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:13.870
We never do an hour.

69
00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:15.830
Hand up to speak.

70
00:06:16.460 --> 00:06:17.500
What?

71
00:06:17.670 --> 00:06:20.500
We never do an hour.
You always say that.


72
00:06:20.670 --> 00:06:24.590
Teachers say we do an hour's class
but we never do.


73
00:06:26.550 --> 00:06:30.350
Eight thirty to 9:25
doesn't make an hour.


74
00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:32.680
All right, it's 55 minutes.

75
00:06:32.850 --> 00:06:35.230
That's an important point.

76
00:06:35.390 --> 00:06:38.520
Stop saying other schools do an hour.

77
00:06:38.690 --> 00:06:40.570
They don't.

78
00:06:40.730 --> 00:06:44.610
All I'm saying is that we waste time.
Like now.


79
00:06:44.780 --> 00:06:48.660
To start with,
take out a sheet of paper...


80
00:06:48.820 --> 00:06:52.370
...fold it in two
so that it can stand...

81
00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:55.250
...on the edge of your desk clearly...

82
00:06:55.410 --> 00:06:59.080
...and, using block capitals...

83
00:06:59.250 --> 00:07:01.790
...write your full name.

84
00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:03.300
Why write our names?

85
00:07:03.510 --> 00:07:05.210
To know who you are.

86
00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:06.880
But you know us.

87
00:07:07.050 --> 00:07:08.470
We had you last year.

88
00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:12.510
Esmeralda,
half of the kids here are new.


89
00:07:12.680 --> 00:07:16.100
Be happy. That way,
people will know your name.


90
00:07:16.270 --> 00:07:17.390
I'm not doing it.

91
00:07:17.560 --> 00:07:20.350
I won't if you don't.

92
00:07:20.900 --> 00:07:21.940
You're right.

93
00:07:22.110 --> 00:07:25.320
For those of you who don't
know me, I'm Mr. Marin.


94
00:07:25.530 --> 00:07:26.990
Ms. Marin.

95
00:07:27.150 --> 00:07:28.860
- A marine?
- Very funny.


96
00:07:29.030 --> 00:07:30.570
Corny.

97
00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:34.660
He wiped you out, sir.

98
00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:38.250
Come on, it shouldn't take so long.

99
00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:43.250
Five minutes to write a name.

100
00:07:43.420 --> 00:07:45.170
It's ridiculous.

101
00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:10.400
A biscuit for the first day?

102
00:08:10.570 --> 00:08:11.950
I'm okay, thanks.

103
00:08:14.950 --> 00:08:18.410
Rachel, a biscuit will buck you up.

104
00:08:22.420 --> 00:08:23.500
All right.

105
00:08:23.670 --> 00:08:25.250
"Witty."

106
00:08:25.420 --> 00:08:27.050
That's a word...

107
00:08:27.210 --> 00:08:29.840
...we'll try to explain later.

108
00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:32.130
Are there any other words...

109
00:08:32.300 --> 00:08:35.930
...that you don't understand?

110
00:08:36.100 --> 00:08:37.140
Burak.

111
00:08:37.310 --> 00:08:39.520
The word "condescension."

112
00:08:39.690 --> 00:08:42.060
Yes, that's a complicated word.

113
00:08:42.230 --> 00:08:44.150
Do you have any idea...

114
00:08:44.310 --> 00:08:46.440
...what that might mean?

115
00:08:46.610 --> 00:08:48.730
A vague idea but I'm not sure.

116
00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:50.990
You're not sure?

117
00:08:51.150 --> 00:08:54.280
We'll talk about that later then.

118
00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:56.080
Yes, Damien?

119
00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:57.580
"Argentite."

120
00:08:57.740 --> 00:09:00.500
Argentite. What does that mean?

121
00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:03.460
It's people who live in Argentina.

122
00:09:03.630 --> 00:09:06.340
Right, the inhabitants of Argentina.

123
00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:08.880
Of course not.

124
00:09:09.460 --> 00:09:11.550
Damien, who lives in Argentina?

125
00:09:11.720 --> 00:09:13.380
The Argentites.

126
00:09:13.550 --> 00:09:15.050
In a soccer match...

127
00:09:15.220 --> 00:09:17.810
...Argentina's players are called...

128
00:09:17.970 --> 00:09:19.850
Footballers.

129
00:09:21.230 --> 00:09:22.310
Let's move on.

130
00:09:22.810 --> 00:09:26.230
Any other difficult words
in this text?


131
00:09:27.520 --> 00:09:28.770
Henriette?

132
00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:33.990
Is there anything
that you didn't understand?


133
00:09:40.330 --> 00:09:43.580
"Henceforth."

134
00:09:43.750 --> 00:09:46.330
Thanks for the prompt, Samantha.

135
00:09:49.960 --> 00:09:54.180
I think that will do.
Let's take a look at these words.


136
00:09:54.340 --> 00:09:57.010
All right. "Austrian."

137
00:09:57.180 --> 00:10:00.720
Wei was the one
who picked the word "Austrian."


138
00:10:00.890 --> 00:10:02.140
Yes, Esmeralda.

139
00:10:02.310 --> 00:10:04.690
We all know what "Austrian" is.

140
00:10:05.060 --> 00:10:08.650
- People from Austria.
- Wei doesn't know and--


141
00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:10.940
Maybe, but everyone else knows.

142
00:10:11.110 --> 00:10:12.570
We get the message.

143
00:10:12.740 --> 00:10:14.570
You didn't know "misleading"...

144
00:10:14.740 --> 00:10:17.990
...so you're not really
in any position to talk.


145
00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:20.990
But everyone knows what "Austrian" means.

146
00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:23.200
Nobody's perfect.

147
00:10:24.830 --> 00:10:28.460
"Austrian" is not
a very important word, Wei.


148
00:10:28.630 --> 00:10:31.920
It refers to someone
from the land of Austria...


149
00:10:32.090 --> 00:10:34.420
...which is a pretty tiny country.

150
00:10:34.590 --> 00:10:36.550
We can live without the word.

151
00:10:36.720 --> 00:10:40.550
Can anyone name a famous Austrian?

152
00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:42.640
Mozart.

153
00:10:42.810 --> 00:10:44.600
Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.

154
00:10:44.770 --> 00:10:47.560
- Who?
- Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.


155
00:10:47.730 --> 00:10:51.610
Wolfgang maybe
if he were English, not Austrian.


156
00:10:51.780 --> 00:10:54.280
Any other famous Austrians?

157
00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:58.700
Austria could vanish,
no one would notice.


158
00:10:58.870 --> 00:11:02.280
Seriously, it's south of Germany.
So check a map, Wei.


159
00:11:02.450 --> 00:11:05.080
You'll see where it is.

160
00:11:05.250 --> 00:11:08.580
Souleymane,
can you note the words too?


161
00:11:08.750 --> 00:11:10.130
I forgot my things.

162
00:11:10.290 --> 00:11:13.130
No one can lend you some paper?

163
00:11:13.300 --> 00:11:15.880
- I'll do it at home.
- You'll do it at home.


164
00:11:16.050 --> 00:11:18.930
Sure you will. 
That's your approach.

165
00:11:19.090 --> 00:11:20.300
Only work at home.

166
00:11:20.470 --> 00:11:21.800
I'm serious.

167
00:11:21.970 --> 00:11:24.810
If I could be sure of that--

168
00:11:24.980 --> 00:11:26.890
Don't worry.

169
00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:28.270
It'll be okay.

170
00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:29.480
Thanks.

171
00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:32.860
Let's move on to "succulent."
"Succulent" is a word...


172
00:11:33.030 --> 00:11:36.070
...that we'll try to guess
the meaning of.


173
00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:38.820
What's in "succulent"?

174
00:11:38.990 --> 00:11:40.030
Suck.

175
00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:42.280
Suck off.

176
00:11:43.580 --> 00:11:44.990
Very funny, Boubacar.

177
00:11:45.160 --> 00:11:46.580
Very witty indeed.

178
00:11:48.670 --> 00:11:49.960
Here's a sentence...

179
00:11:50.920 --> 00:11:52.710
...with "succulent."

180
00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:58.130
Bill enjoys a succulent...

181
00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:00.760
...cheeseburger.

182
00:12:00.930 --> 00:12:02.470
Cheeseburgers stink.

183
00:12:04.470 --> 00:12:06.430
- Who said that?
- Me.


184
00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:08.020
Why a cheeseburger?

185
00:12:08.190 --> 00:12:10.940
Well, since you say they stink...

186
00:12:11.100 --> 00:12:14.190
...you think cheeseburgers
aren't succulent.


187
00:12:14.360 --> 00:12:16.530
Maybe, but they're crap.

188
00:12:16.690 --> 00:12:21.160
Okay, but what I just said
should have made the penny drop.


189
00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:22.490
What does that mean?

190
00:12:22.660 --> 00:12:25.240
- What?
- The penny thing.


191
00:12:27.160 --> 00:12:29.370
To make the penny drop.

192
00:12:29.540 --> 00:12:31.420
No one knows the expression?

193
00:12:31.580 --> 00:12:33.830
If the penny drops,
it means you understand.


194
00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:35.710
When I say...

195
00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:40.340
...if cheeseburgers stink,
they're not succulent...


196
00:12:40.510 --> 00:12:43.890
...that should help you see
what "succulent" means.


197
00:12:44.050 --> 00:12:47.140
- What's with the Bills?
- What bills?


198
00:12:47.350 --> 00:12:48.680
The name Bill.

199
00:12:49.180 --> 00:12:51.480
You always use weird names.

200
00:12:51.650 --> 00:12:54.980
Weird? A recent U.S. president
was called Bill.


201
00:12:55.150 --> 00:12:59.570
Why don't you use Aissata or Rachid
or Ahmed or...?


202
00:12:59.740 --> 00:13:01.650
You always use whitey names.

203
00:13:01.860 --> 00:13:04.120
- What names?
- Honky names.


204
00:13:04.280 --> 00:13:06.080
What's a honky?

205
00:13:06.240 --> 00:13:10.080
Honkies, Frenchies, frogs.

206
00:13:10.250 --> 00:13:11.410
You're not French?

207
00:13:11.580 --> 00:13:13.920
- No, I'm not French.
- I didn't know.


208
00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:16.250
I am, but not proud of it.

209
00:13:16.420 --> 00:13:18.340
Fine, I'm not either.

210
00:13:18.510 --> 00:13:19.710
Wiped him out.

211
00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:21.220
Why use these names?

212
00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:26.260
Khoumba,
if I start choosing names...


213
00:13:26.430 --> 00:13:29.220
...to suit all your origins,
it'll never end.


214
00:13:29.390 --> 00:13:30.930
Just change a little.

215
00:13:33.020 --> 00:13:35.310
What do you suggest?

216
00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:37.610
Aissata. Fatou.

217
00:13:37.770 --> 00:13:40.570
No, Aissata.

218
00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:14.140
Excuse me.
You have class 4/3 in French?


219
00:14:14.310 --> 00:14:16.060
I'm class supervisor too.

220
00:14:16.230 --> 00:14:18.900
Know what book you'll be reading?

221
00:14:19.070 --> 00:14:21.480
No, I haven't decided.

222
00:14:22.570 --> 00:14:27.360
In history, I'll start
with the Ancien Régime.


223
00:14:27.530 --> 00:14:29.910
If you want to link into that...

224
00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:33.080
...what kind of books are there?

225
00:14:34.540 --> 00:14:37.790
The Enlightenment will be tough for them.

226
00:14:37.960 --> 00:14:40.960
How about Voltaire? Is he tough?

227
00:14:41.130 --> 00:14:43.010
He's not easy.

228
00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:45.220
Candide is simple.

229
00:14:46.220 --> 00:14:47.840
Not in their year.

230
00:14:48.470 --> 00:14:50.300
Zadig.

231
00:14:50.470 --> 00:14:52.140
Yes, but...

232
00:14:52.310 --> 00:14:54.310
It'd be tough.

233
00:15:28.390 --> 00:15:32.220
- Twenty seconds to go.
- No, sir, please.


234
00:15:32.390 --> 00:15:34.470
We haven't finished.

235
00:15:34.640 --> 00:15:37.560
We can't spend two hours
on the imperfect.


236
00:15:41.190 --> 00:15:43.570
Dalla, I can give you the time.

237
00:15:47.240 --> 00:15:48.950
Sir, my pen keeps leaking.

238
00:15:49.660 --> 00:15:51.660
- It's crap.
- Who has a handkerchief?


239
00:15:51.830 --> 00:15:53.740
Me.

240
00:15:53.910 --> 00:15:55.490
Rabah.

241
00:15:55.660 --> 00:15:57.540
Ask before you stand.

242
00:15:58.790 --> 00:16:00.830
- May I?
- Yes.


243
00:16:03.380 --> 00:16:06.300
- Gently, okay.
- The perv.


244
00:16:06.460 --> 00:16:07.720
He touched her tits.

245
00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:10.260
Just give him the handkerchief.

246
00:16:11.550 --> 00:16:12.640
Spare us your comments.

247
00:16:12.800 --> 00:16:14.890
Goddamn pedophile.

248
00:16:16.770 --> 00:16:19.060
- Quiet.
- Sir.


249
00:16:21.560 --> 00:16:23.690
Why the imperfect indicative?

250
00:16:24.730 --> 00:16:26.690
Cut it out.

251
00:16:27.780 --> 00:16:31.530
- Why not just imperfect?
- Quiet, Souleymane.


252
00:16:31.700 --> 00:16:34.700
All right, Esmeralda,
why the indicative?


253
00:16:34.870 --> 00:16:38.160
If I knew, I wouldn't ask.

254
00:16:38.330 --> 00:16:39.410
I can imagine.

255
00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:43.330
Anyone know why we specify
the imperfect indicative?


256
00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:45.500
Why not just the imperfect?

257
00:16:45.670 --> 00:16:48.380
- Nassim.
- May I wash my hands?


258
00:16:48.590 --> 00:16:51.180
Go on, wash them
and get it over with.


259
00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:53.640
Make it quick.

260
00:16:53.800 --> 00:16:55.510
He'll take a week.

261
00:16:56.470 --> 00:16:58.520
- I'll go with him.
- Enough.


262
00:17:00.350 --> 00:17:05.110
The imperfect indicative is different
than another imperfect.


263
00:17:06.110 --> 00:17:07.860
Which imperfect is that?

264
00:17:08.320 --> 00:17:11.030
- Agame?
- The imperfect subjunctive.


265
00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:12.490
Exactly.

266
00:17:12.660 --> 00:17:14.450
The imperfect subjunctive.

267
00:17:14.620 --> 00:17:17.160
